Ginger

Zingiber officinale

Aromatic Plants
Author: Keshab Raj Paudel
Published: 13/05/2024
Read Time: 4 minutes
Category: Aromatic Plants
Location: Pune

Description

Ginger (Zingiber officinale) is a herbaceous perennial plant widely cultivated for its thick, aromatic, and branched underground rhizome used as a spice and medicine. The rhizome has a brown outer layer and pale yellow interior with a spicy, citrusy aroma. The plant grows pseudostems about 3 to 4 feet tall made from tightly wrapped leaf bases bearing narrow, lanceolate medium-green leaves arranged in two ranks. The flowers appear on a separate stalk and form dense, cone-shaped spikes with pale yellow petals and purplish edges. The rhizomes are juicy and fleshy when young, becoming more fibrous and pungent with maturity. Ginger thrives in humid, tropical, and subtropical climates, prefers well-drained fertile soil, and requires moderate water and partial shade to full sun. It is widely used in cooking.

This herbal perennial is also known for its beautiful flowering spikes, making it a popular ornamental plant in subtropical gardens.

Medicinal Properties

Anti-inflammatory antioxidant analgesic antispasmodic antiemetic antimicrobial antipyretic digestive stimulant immunomodulatory

Common Uses

  • 1)Fresh or dried rhizome used as spice or decoction
  • 2)Ginger tea for relief from cold and cough
  • 3(Powder used in digestive formulations
  • 4)Oil and extracts used in massage for joint pain
  • 5Ginger juice for nausea and indigestion

Growing Information

Growing Conditions

Prefers well-drained, fertile loamy soil, Partial shade to full sun exposure,Needs humid tropical or subtropical climate,Requires loose, rich soil with organic matter

Water Requirements

Moderate; consistent moisture needed but avoid waterloggingTemperature Range: 20C to 30C considered optimal for growth

Temperature Range

20C to 30C considered optimal for growth

Harvesting Tips

Harvest rhizomes 8-10 months after planting when leaves turn yellow and dry; gentle digging recommended to avoid damage

Preparation Methods

Fresh rhizome can be peeled, grated, or juiced for direct useDried rhizome powder used in medicines and spice blends Oil extracts prepared by steam distillation from rhizomesGinger gel and syrups made from fresh juice and extracts

Land Preparation: Plough the land 3-5 times to bring the soil to a fine tilth. Use crosswise harrowing to make the soil loose and friable. Apply well-decomposed farmyard manure (FYM) about 15-20 tons per hectare during final land preparation.Bed and Ridge Formation: Prepare raised beds or ridges about 15-30 cm height. Ridges are generally spaced 40-45 cm apart with furrows or drainage channels in between to avoid waterlogging.Propagation: Use healthy rhizome setts (seed rhizomes) of weight 20-30 g each with 2-3 well-developed buds. Treat seed rhizomes with fungicide like Dithane M-45 or hot water treatment before planting.

Chemical Compounds

Gingerols shogaols paradols zingiberene beta-bisabolene zingerone volatile oils
